initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories: De-Graft: Olly, you've got a big challenge ahead of you! How are you feeling about representing the UK this year? Olly Alexander: To be honest, I'm feeling a mix of emotions. There's a lot of pressure to perform well, but at the same time, I'm really excited to be part of this incredible event. De-Graft: You've been working hard on your song, Dizzy. Can you tell us a bit about the creative process behind it?

Olly Alexander: Yeah, I've been pouring my heart and soul into this song. I think what really inspired me was the idea of capturing the feeling of being in a club, surrounded by the energy of the music and the crowd. I wanted to write something that would make people feel like they're part of something special, something that would take them away from their daily worries and just let them have fun. De-Graft: That sounds amazing. What's the story behind the lyrics?

Olly Alexander: Ah, yeah! The lyrics are really personal to me, to be honest. I was going through a tough time, and I was feeling really lost and alone. But then I went to this festival, and I saw all these people dancing and singing along to the music, and it just hit me - we're all in this together, you know? We're all just trying to find our way, and music has the power to bring us together like nothing else can. So, the lyrics are all about that feeling of unity and release. It's like, we can all come together and just lose ourselves in the music, you know?

It's like, the music becomes this kind of sanctuary, where you can let go of all your worries and just be free. And I think that's what I was trying to capture with those lyrics - this sense of freedom and togetherness.

It's funny, when I was writing the song, I didn't even realize that's what I was going for, but now that I think about it, it makes total sense. Because, for me, music has always been that one place where I can be myself, without apology or expectation.

It's where I can be vulnerable and raw, and just let my emotions shine through, without fear of judgment or criticism. And I think that's what people relate to most about my music, because they know that I'm not trying to be someone I'm not, I'm just being genuine and true to myself.

When I'm on stage, I feel like I can finally be myself, without the mask of fame or celebrity attached to me. I can connect with the people in the audience on a real level, and I think that's what makes my performances so special. It's like we're all in this together, you know?

And I think that's what I love about this tour, too - we're not just performing for the crowd, we're performing with them. We're all in this together, sharing this moment of pure energy and connection.

It's like we're all connected by this invisible thread, and that's what makes the experience so intense and unforgettable. Everyone's sweating, everyone's dancing, and everyone's singing along at the top of their lungs - it's like we're all speaking the same language, you know?

And in that moment, nothing else matters, just the music and the people and the feeling of being alive. It's like we're all lost in our own little world, and the only way to find our way out is to let go and let the music take over.
